<TEXT>
us warships do not routinely monitor radio 
communications between airliners and air traffic controllers in the 
persian gulf and have not regularly done so since the uss vincennes 
shot down iran air flight 655 say pentagon officials 
iran says the a300 airbus had communicated with air traffic 
control at bandar abbas iran in english the international 
language for airlines and that if the vincennes had been 
listening it might not have mistaken the airliner for an iranian 
f14 fighter 
iran has asked the united nations security council and 
international civil aviation organization to review the july 3 
incident the pentagon is conducting its own investigation which 
spokesman dan howard has said will determine what radio and radar 
information was available to the skipper of the vincennes capt 
will c rogers iii 
other pentagon officials said wednesday that as a standard 
practice us warships in the gulf monitor three communications 
channels in addition to those used for transmissions among 
themselves 
the channels routinely monitored are a bridgetobridge 
frequency used by civilian and military ship captains a civilian 
distress channel used by ships and planes and a military distress 
channel used by military ships and planes said one official who 
spoke on condition of anonymity 
there are many many radio frequencies used it would take a 
heck of a lot of people to monitor all of them howard told 
reporters last week 
and on wednesday navy sources who spoke on condition of 
anonymity said us warships do not monitor the various wavelengths 
used by air traffic controllers 
air traffic control communications may have been monitored by 
the national security agency the government organization that 
collects electronic intelligence however nsa does not publicly 
discuss its activities and it was not clear whether any 
intelligence it gathered would be disclosed along with the results 
of the pentagon investigation officials said 
ships in the us gulf fleet have not been ordered to change 
their routine monitoring nor has additional radio equipment been 
supplied to them since the incident the sources said 
public statements by senior pentagon officials indicate that the 
single vhf monitoring station on the vincennes was used during the 
incident to send warnings to the approaching aircraft 
the chairman of the joint chiefs of staff adm william j crowe 
jr in a news conference hours after the shootdown said we 
warned him the iran air pilot on the civilian air distress net 
three times in these few minutes and four times on the military 
air distress net 
crowe also said he was not aware of any radio communications 
from the airliner that were intercepted by naval forces in the 
gulf but he said we have contacted airliners before and we have 
had them respond 
the pentagon investigation team headed by rear adm william m 
fogarty has received a computer analysis of the tapes of the 
vincennes electronic system that theoretically will tell them 
whether the cruiser was monitoring iranian air traffic control 
communications us sources in the gulf say 
there are 21 possible tape channels on the ship they can be 
switched to various systems i do not know which systems there were 
recording and which ones were turned on at this particular time 
howard said but it does have the capability to record both 
external communications and internal from station to station 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

