<TEXT>
ridding the nations nuclear weapons plants of 
contamination will be a monstrous problem but must be done a 
senator said after releasing a study that put the price tag at more 
than 130 billion 
were endangering people on the bases were endangering 
workers were endangering people in surrounding communities 
sen john glenn dohio said wednesday as he released a 
congressional study estimating the cleanup costs 
the 130 billion estimate could jump by an additional 25 
billion if production at the plants is expanded capacity is 
relocated or both the general accounting office study said 
we just have to do this cleanup glenn said its going to 
be monstrous its going to be expensive but we have to do it 
the report which was requested by glenn and released at a 
hearing held by the senate governmental affairs committee comes on 
the heels of cost estimates compiled by the us department of 
energy and made public july 1 
the department said cleaning up contamination and correcting 
other problems at 17 major defense plants could cost between 40 
billion and 70 billion and jump to as high as 110 billion in 
order to maintain standards through the year 2045 
however the gao computed additional costs in its estimates 
including plant improvements and the disposal of radioactive waste 
the installations which are scattered across the country 
produce nuclear materials and weapons for us defense needs 
the gao survey focused on the departments major defense plants 
including the savannah river plant in south carolina the feed 
materials production center and the mound plant both in ohio the 
rocky flats plant in colorado the y12 plant in tennessee hanford 
reservation in washington state the kansas city electronics plant 
the pinellas plant in florida the pantex plant in texas sandia 
and los alamos national laboratories both in new mexico the 
nevada test site idaho national engineering lab and lawrence 
livermore national lab in california 
the gao did not provide a cost breakdown for each installation 
