<TEXT>
momentum is building in congress to protect a 
hallowed civil war battleground from a massive shopping center 
complex that a developer wants to build next door 
the house interior and insular affairs committee approved a 
measure wednesday authorizing the federal government to seize a 
542acre tract next to the manassas national battlefield park 
the bill a combination of legislation introduced by rep frank 
wolf rva and another bill sponsored by reps michael andrews 
dtexas and robert mrazek dny now moves to the house floor 
after passing the committee by a 2711 vote supporters hope the 
matter will come up for a vote when the house reconvenes after the 
democratic national convention 
critics of the measure including rep ron marlenee rmont 
complained that the bill was too costly but it was approved after 
the panel defeated an amendment offered by marlenee that would have 
added 11000 acres to the custer battlefield national monument 
near billings mont 
the house committee vote came one day after a 106 billion 
transportation bill passed by the senate included a provision to 
block any federal money from being used for highway construction 
associated with the proposed william center development 
a similar measure had already been included in transportation 
legislation approved by the house and supporters of the provision 
predict it will survive final legislative changes made by house and 
senate members 
congress entered the domain of local zoning officials after 
historians and preservationists complained that the massive 
development would destroy the rural sanctity of the 4600acre park 
where two important civil war battles took place 
developer john t hazel seeks to build a complex including 12 
million square feet of retail space 17 million square feet of 
office space and 560 homes he bought the property in 1985 and 
first proposed a smallscale office park for the site then 
expanded his plans to the current concept once prince william 
county va officials relaxed zoning restrictions on the property 
the park is the site of the first and second battles of 
manassas which were both confederate victories 
</TEXT>
