attention to any unjustified increases during the drought 
consumer federation of america affiliates around the nation will 
survey the price of staples each month reported cfa executive 
director stephen brobeck 
we want to help prevent any unjustifiable increases in the 
name of drought damage said ellen haas of the group public voice 
for food and health policy 
assistant agriculture secretary ewen wilson said tuesday that 
the drought is expected to boost food prices 3 percent to 5 percent 
this year next year food prices could rise another 2 percent to 3 
percent in addition to any inflation increases department 
officials have speculated 
brobeck said that the price surveys will cover breakfast cereal 
beef poultry pasta canned and frozen vegetables cooking oils 
margarine sugar and coffee 
he said that the initial survey next week will be used to 
establish baseline prices and that monthly comparison surveys will 
be continued through at least october 
