<TEXT>
the tiniest baby ever to receive a liver 
transplant died thursday two days after doctors divided a donated 
organ between him and another baby in the first us operation of 
its type a spokesman said 
twelveweekold joseph kovach died of heart failure at wyler 
childrens hospital at the university of chicago medical center 
spokesman john easton said 
the boys heart had stopped briefly after the transplant and he 
later suffered kidney and lung failure 
the other baby a 7monthold girl was doing very well but 
was listed in critical and stable condition easton said 
the kovach baby of geneva ill weighed only 42 pounds 
tuesday when he received the transplant which doctors regarded as 
a longshot for saving his life but his only hope said his 
physician peter f whitington 
joseph had previously undergone openheart surgery to correct a 
birth defect but his heart was still weak and the stress of the 
second operation was too much whitington said 
his death will not discourage subsequent double liver 
transplants which could help other youngsters too small to 
accommodate adult livers and likely to die while awaiting scarcer 
childrens organs whitington said 
technically this is not a setback his liver was functioning 
very well this morning even just before he died whitington 
said of course that is not important to joseph kovach 
what we showed with this pair is that its clearly technically 
feasible whitington said we did it under the worst of 
circumstances with a very sick very small baby that needed a 
graft new organ we never would have gotten without a reduction 
in the size of the donor organ 
double liver transplants have been performed previously in 
europe involving adult donors but no double liver transplants had 
been done previously in the united states easton said 
whitington said he told the boys parents that any complications 
at all would result in the childs death and that if it all went 
perfectly there was a small chance he would make it 
joseph suffered from cirrhosis a type of liver damage that can 
exist at birth from an unknown cause 
he was the first child of patty and donald kovach a comptroller 
for a chicago firm easton said 
the other youngster jaclyn manrose of crystal lake ill had a 
hereditary defect called alpha1antitrypsin deficiency an 
insufficent amount of an enzyme that can lead to hepatitis or 
cirrhosis 
jaclyn is one of three children of kathleen and bob manrose a 
maintenance specialist with united airlines easton said 
jaclyn and joseph received the divided liver of a 1yearold 
illinois child who died in an accident the university said 
two younger infants have received new livers at the university 
of pittsburghs transplant center but both babies ages 16 days 
and 3 weeks weighed more than 6 pounds easton said 
