<TEXT>
michael dukakis is the democratic nomineetobe 
but jesse jackson is getting all the attention at least in the 
week before the national convention 
dukakis tended state business in boston on thursday while 
jackson launched a threeday bus trip from chicago to atlanta to 
wrap up his presidential campaign 
dukakis made private phone calls seeking reconciliation with 
jackson jackson made public requests for mediation by former 
president jimmy carter 
youd almost think jackson is the one who won the nomination and 
dukakis is the alsoran 
and thats precisely the trap the massachusetts governor must 
avoid 
above all dukakis needs to come out the atlanta convention next 
friday looking like a man in control of his party and of his own 
destiny 
because dukakis is still a relative unknown to millions of 
voters the sights and impressions from the four nights of 
convention activities on the television screens of america will 
play a major role in shaping the voters thoughts 
the last thing dukakis needs next week is a constant drumbeat of 
questions about what will jesse do competing with the music 
inside the convention hall 
it is certain that dukakis doesnt need jacksons votes inside 
the omni next week to run the convention the massachusetts 
governor has plenty of delegates to stay in charge 
but dukakis does need the votes of millions of jacksons 
supporters outside the hall to beat republican george bush on nov 
8 
at the same time he must avoid the appearance that he is 
pandering to jackson or caving in to the civil rights leaders 
demands 
the appearance of pandering to jackson and his supporters 
damaged walter mondale in his 1984 campaign for the white house 
planting doubts about mondales toughness and his ability to handle 
the demands of special interests 
on thursday jackson demonstrated once again why it is so hard 
to negotiate with this man who has honed the tools of public 
relations and electronic media into powerful bargaining tools 
the preacherturnedpolitician demanded center stage again with 
a single stroke 
it grabs the headlines with a wellknown name 
it puts two prominent men on the spot dukakis and carter 
carter would certainly like to be helpful but how to do so is a 
tricky question 
dukakis cant very well ignore a former president but he surely 
doesnt want carter involved in this either intermediaries just 
complicate things 
moreover democrats dont really want carter in the spotlight 
very long at this convention 
the memories of carters years in the white house are not ones 
that dukakis and democrats want to revive soaring prices gasoline 
lines and iranian hostages were not a pretty picture 
this latest squabble between the campaigns may simply turn out 
to be a little entertainment before the main event 
jackson gets to town on saturday afternoon and dukakis on 
sunday the two will probably meet privately 
what is said at the meeting and the pictures that the nation 
sees after it could well set the tone for the entire convention 
</TEXT>
