up with producingstate democrats in an impasse that if not 
resolved could leave the commission paralyzed for lack of a quorum 
the occasion was a hearing on the nomination of elizabeth anne 
moler to the commission whose confirmation senators said is not in 
question she is a 12year veteran natural gas expert on the 
committee staff who is supported by all the committee members 
the fivemember commission regulates natural gas pipelines some 
wellhead gas pricing oil pipelines hydroelectric dams and 
wholesale electricity sales and oversees state regulation of small 
power producers the commission must always have a 32 party split 
currently in favor of the republicans 
members may serve for up to a year after their fouryear terms 
expire if no successor has been confirmed 
if confirmed ms moler would replace democrat charles stalon 
who has been serving since his term expired last october 
despite a warning from committee chairman bennett johnston 
dla and ranking republican james mcclure ridaho that stalon 
could not be confirmed again president reagan nominated stalon to 
fill a vacant seat formerly held by a texas democrat for a term 
expiring in october 1989 
if you look at the composition of the commission its obvious 
there is a demand for a seat for a producingstate democrat and 
confirmation of stalon and moler would leave no room for one 
