<TEXT>
duke ellington was such a prolific composer and 
profound influence on american music that it takes the pbs series 
american masters two installments to tell his story 
the first half of producerdirector terry carters vivid 
portrayal a duke named ellington airs monday night on the 
public broadcasting service the second half can be seen next 
monday july 25 
the documentary includes rare performance footage from europe 
never before seen in the united states and interviews with many of 
the musicians who played in ellingtons band which stayed together 
for a record 47 years 
ellington who died in 1974 began his career in harlem he says 
in interview footage that there was a lot of tough competition from 
the many pianists on the busy music scene guys like count basie 
willie the lion smith and james p johnson 
but im lucky ellington says everybody liked me 
suave handsome and charismatic ellington was also a shrewd 
businessman who entered into a productive partnership with music 
publisher irving mills it was mills who was instrumental in 
getting ellington a gig at the cotton club the documentary 
includes tape of an announcer introducing ellington as the 
greatest living master of jungle music 
ellingtons association with mills according to ellington 
helped break down racial barriers in the music industry and at a 
time when blacks were being insulted by hollywood stereotypes 
ellington and the band appeared in their first movie in 1930 
check and double check ellingtons cool sophisticated style 
gave black americans a positive selfimage 
it seems he was as charismatic to his musicians as he was to his 
fans 
i consider myself privileged to sit in duke ellingtons band 
for 28 years says russell procope any musician you talk to 
whether white black grizzled or gray wanted to play with duke 
ellingtons band believe me 
in 1943 ellington hired clarinetist jimmy hamilton whose 
smooth benny goodmanish sound was a departure from the new 
orleansstyle jazz that was prevalent among black musicians in an 
interview hamilton recalls his reluctance at joining ellingtons 
band because he was working well enough and didnt want to go on 
the road 
he also recalls with relish how he would practice constantly to 
keep up with ellingtons increasingly complex compositions 
he put some music up and id say hey thats difficult man 
i dont know if i can make that you were always trying to stay a 
little ahead of him because he was going to try to get you sooner 
or later 
hamilton said he managed the piece quite well and ellington 
took the same music to goodman who without benefit of practice 
didnt do such a good job ellington came back gloating according 
to hamilton and said ah i found out bennys human 
ellingtons relationship with sax player johnny hodges was not 
so genial according to critic leonard feather hodges riffs would 
sometimes get turned into compositions by ellington and hodges 
felt he was due some proceeds when ellington would play the piece 
said feather johnny would start making motions with his hands 
like counting money you know and that went on actually on the 
bandstand 
part 2 which follows ellingtons later career opens with 
ellington and the band playing the classic take the a train 
which in fact was written by collaborator billy strayhorn 
that number is followed by another classic mood indigo 
i think we played that every night for 28 years said 
procope i never got tired of it because every night it was like 
the first time 
in an interview ellington is asked about his relationship to 
his people the people he responds thats the better 
word the people rather than my people becuase the people are my 
people 
</TEXT>
