<TEXT>
japan said thursday its trade figures with the 
united states have improved dramatically in the past six months and 
predicted the trend will continue for the rest of the year 
overall the trade surplus with the united states was down 149 
percent during the period from january through june compared with 
the same period last year according to statistics from the foreign 
ministry 
imports rose 408 percent in dollar terms while exports were up 
only 58 percent 
part of the improvement was attributable to a decline in the 
value of the dollar which makes imports in dollar terms seem 
greater 
in yen terms imports were up 197 percent while exports were 
up 99 percent 
in overall trade imports were up 343 percent in dollar terms 
and exports were up 157 percent the balance of trade 
internationally declined by 159 percent 
a foreign ministry spokesman who demanded anonymity said he 
was pleased with the latest figures and said japan was working hard 
to solve international trade problems 
he said japan in the first half of this year had made 
significant progress in resolving thorny trade issues such as beef 
and citrus quotas with the united states a new science and 
technology agreement with washington and an agreement to open its 
construction industry to foreign competition 
according to the trade figures imports of wood products from 
the united states were up a sharp 52 percent foodstuff imports 
were up 34 percent and machinery imports were up 58 percent 
the official said he expected these trends to continue but said 
we cant be too complacent he said twoway trade cannot always 
be free from friction but he said japan has shown to the world 
it is capable of dealing with these issues 
