<DOCNO> AP880714-0247 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the chicago board options exchange smarting 
from a 50 percent downturn in options trading since the oct 19 
stock market collapse is trying to persuade brokers and investors 
to return to the market 
the market is dispatching teams to 30 cities to contact brokers 
explain what happened and promote stock options sales to put a 
floor under losses for potential investors 
were trying to rebuild the business said james emerson a 
marketing consultant with the exchange who will travel to san 
antonio memphis and new orleans next week 
after a fiveyear bull market when confidence in the financial 
markets blossomed to an alltime high individual investors were 
badly shaken by the october debacle and have been slow to return 
shortly after oct 19 options trading volume on the chicago 
board options exchange fell by 50 percent emerson said trading 
has slowly improved but has yet to approach preoctober levels he 
said 
individual investors make up about 75 percent of the exchanges 
clientele its recovery has been somewhat slower than the 
institutiondriven stock market 
emerson says the chicago board options exchange which accounts 
for 55 percent of all listed options traded in the united states 
has slashed staff cutting the fat down to the muscle 
the most noticeable change is that consumers are less eager to 
enter the risky business of call and put options 
a call option is the right to buy 100 shares of a security 
based on the expectation that a stock will rise in price a put 
option is the right to sell 100 shares of a security on the 
expectation that the stocks price will fall 
to counter consumer fears emerson suggests that brokerages use 
options to reduce risk and make a portfolio more conservative 
for instance an investor might buy a certain companys stock 
then purchase put options on that same stock the strategy puts a 
floor on losses regardless of whether the stock price rises or 
falls 
were not presenting anything thats brand new emerson 
said but by reminding brokers about the advantages of options 
trading he hopes many of them will start calling clients again 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

