<TEXT>
federal home loan mortgage corps preferred 
stock soared in heavy trading thursday when the first in a series 
of ownership restrictions were lifted in a move that could bring 
fresh capital to the savings and loan industry 
in composite nationwide trading of issues listed on the new york 
stock exchange the shares jumped 3275 a share to 13275 the 
first opportunity savings and loan institutions have had to boost 
their holdings beyond 150000 shares 
analysts have speculated the stock could trade as high as 200 a 
share 
the board of the federal home loan mortgage corp known as 
freddie mac approved a plan wednesday to increase the number of 
shares that savings institutions may own and to allow the public to 
own shares beginning jan 1 
freddie mac is a congressionally created entity that buys home 
mortgages from savings insitutions and other lenders and packages 
them into securities for resale to investors thus making more 
money available for home buyers 
freddie mac voting stock is owned by the federal home loan bank 
system which in turn is owned by the nations savings 
institutions its perferred stock which has no voting power is 
held now only by savings institutions 
under terms of the plan approved wednesday the limits on the 
number of shares a single stockholder may own were immediately 
lifted from 150000 to 300000 the limit will rise to 450000 on 
oct 1 and to 600000 on jan 1 
savings institutions will be permitted until nov 30 to exchange 
restricted shares for shares that public investors will be 
permitted to buy after jan 1 the institutions will have to pay a 
7ashare fee for the exchange 
freddie mac has 15 million preferred shares outstanding 
ownership restrictions on the 100000 outstanding shares of voting 
stock are unaffected and remain in place 
analysts said the stock is an attractive buy because of the 
earning power behind it 
as it trades it will trade up in value which means the value 
of the holdings of the sampls that own stock will go up and boost 
their capital positions which is what they desperately need 
said charles vincent an analyst at provident national bank in 
philadelphia 
in addition vincent noted that since freddie mac is a 
government agency there is virtually no risk in holding the shares 
vincent said the individual thrifts must choose whether to 
sell their shares to boost their capital position or hold on to 
show an appreciation on their investment 
