three big us banking companies reported thursday that they 
were profitable in the second quarter after posting losses a year 
earlier 
the trio chemical banking corp security pacific corp and 
bank of new york co had sustained heavy losses in the second 
quarter of 1987 from writeoffs for potential losses on loans to 
developing countries 
first city bancorp of texas meanwhile which recently received 
a 970 million federal bailout reported net income of 172 
million for the 72day period immediately following its 16 
billion reorganization 
the restructured bank based in houston said net income for the 
initial period ending june 30 was 66 cents a share total assets as 
of june 30 were 113 billion loans were 63 billion deposits 
were 91 billion and shareholders equity was 586 million 
chemical banking the nations fourthlargest bank holding 
company said it earned 1277 million or 198 a share compared 
with a net loss of 11 billion in the second quarter of 1987 
if the loanloss provisions hadnt been made in the second 
quarter of last year new yorkbased chemical would have earned 
764 million or 121 a share it said 
for the first six months of the year chemical had net income of 
2532 million or 393 a share compared with a net loss of 10 
billion in the same period last year 
the bank said its earnings in the latest quarter and six months 
were due to increases in net interest income trust fees and other 
banking fees gains from venture capital activities and higher 
profits from bond trading 
the company changed its name in late april from chemical new 
york corp 
seventhranked security pacific reported a profit of 1543 
million or 136 a share compared to a net loss of 1902 million 
in the second quarter of last year 
the 1987 secondquarter results were dragged down by a onetime 
558 million provision for bad loans to developing countries this 
year the company has cut its nontrade developing country debts by 
40 percent said chairman richard j flamson iii 
in the latest quarter the company posted net interest income of 
6622 million up from 5991 million in the second quarter of 
1987 
